## 15. PUNCTUATION

### Tier A — banned in running text:
- **Exclamation marks (!)** — no sentence in a thesis ends with one
- **Ellipses (…)** — not used in running text
- **Em dashes (—) used decoratively** — see below

### Tier B — em dashes:
Em dashes are heavily overused in LLM-generated text and should be avoided.
In most cases, a cleaner alternative exists:

| ✗ With em dash | ✓ Scientific alternative |
|---|---|
| "The method — widely used — has limits." | "The method is widely used but has limits." |
| "Three factors matter — cost, time, quality." | "Three factors matter: cost, time, and quality." |
| "The result — surprisingly — confirms H1." | "The result confirms H1, which is notable given the baseline." |

Use an em dash only when no other construction adequately serves the purpose,
and only once or twice in the entire thesis.

### Question marks:
Rhetorical questions in running text should be avoided. If a question is posed,
the answer must follow immediately. Acceptable use: explicitly formulated
research questions.

---

## 16. COMMON ERRORS — DIRECT COMPARISON

| ✗ Weak | ✓ Strong | Rule violated |
|---|---|---|
| "The results are very interesting." | "The results contradict hypothesis H2 by showing X." | Subjective evaluation |
| "It was found that it is possible that…" | "It is possible that…" | Double distancing |
| "This thesis attempts to show…" | "This thesis shows…" | Unmotivated hedging |
| "As mentioned above, X is the case." | "X is the case (cf. Section 2.3)." | Redundancy |
| "It should be noted that the sample is limited." | "The sample comprises n = 50, limiting generalizability to [context]." | Vague filler + missing precision |
| "The model is capable of capturing this." | "The model captures this." | Nominalization |
| "The literature shows that…" | "Scholars argue that…" / "Studies have shown that…" | Anthropomorphism |
| "A wide range of studies confirm this." | "Multiple studies confirm this (Brown, 2019; Chen, 2022)." | Vagueness + missing citation |

